{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478600"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17524"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17524"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.17,0.08,0.36,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112962"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10214"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17524"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94994"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"906"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"5630"},{"type":"tags","id":"9629"},{"type":"tags","id":"13217"},{"type":"tags","id":"13220"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46872"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112962"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department after collapsing during a baseball game. Witnesses report he was struck in the chest by a baseball while batting. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is unconscious. His pulse is absent, and cardiopulmonary resuscitation is in progress. An automated external defibrillator shows ventricular fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely mechanism of this patient\u0027s cardiac arrest?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiac tamponade from sternal fracture","Pre-existing hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","Traumatic aortic rupture","Impact during cardiac repolarisation","Myocardial contusion with coronary artery dissection"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic example of commotio cordis, a rare but potentially fatal condition that occurs predominantly in young male athletes. The condition typically affects children aged 8-18 years due to their more compliant chest walls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpact during cardiac repolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct mechanism. Commotio cordis occurs when a blunt, non-penetrating impact to the precordium occurs during the vulnerable period of cardiac repolarisation (approximately 20 milliseconds before the peak of the T wave). This precise timing triggers ventricular fibrillation even without structural cardiac damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocardial contusion with coronary artery dissection\u003C/strong\u003E typically requires a much more forceful impact and would be unlikely with a baseball strike. Additionally, this mechanism would not explain the immediate onset of ventricular fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETraumatic aortic rupture\u003C/strong\u003E requires significant deceleration forces and would present with signs of shock and mediastinal haemorrhage rather than immediate cardiac arrest with ventricular fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-existing hypertrophic cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E, while an important cause of sudden cardiac death in young athletes, typically presents during exertion rather than immediately following chest impact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac tamponade from sternal fracture\u003C/strong\u003E would develop more gradually and would be unlikely to cause immediate ventricular fibrillation. Additionally, sternal fractures are rare in children due to chest wall compliance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to survival in commotio cordis is immediate recognition and early defibrillation. Preventive measures include age-appropriate protective equipment and safety balls in youth sports.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Commotio cordis occurs when a blunt impact to the chest wall during the vulnerable period of cardiac repolarisation triggers ventricular fibrillation.","Immediate recognition and early defibrillation are critical factors in survival from commotio cordis.","Preventive measures include age-appropriate protective equipment and safety balls in youth sports."],"references":["Okorare O, Alugba G, Olusiji S, Evbayekha EO, Antia AU, Daniel E, Ubokudum D, Adabale OK, Ariaga A. Sudden Cardiac Death: An Update on Commotio Cordis. Cureus. 2023 Apr 24;15(4):e38087. doi: 10.7759/cureus.38087. PMID: 37252546; PMCID: PMC10209547."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94994"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17524"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94994"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T17:17:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-11T21:02:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10214"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112962"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","syn